2026-04-16 12:33:33 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module relay contacts / series connection to output (+) cable'] hypothesis_explanation='The power module is providing a solid ~12 V (LED on and 11.99 V measured on the control-module input +). However, the control-module output + to the load sits at only ~0.36 V relative to ground, even while the relay should be supplying the load. This low but non-zero voltage is consistent with a high-resistance path—typically pitted/burned relay contacts or a defective series connection between the relay’s common and normally‑open contact and the output cable. The behaviour of the main lamp turning off briefly every ~20 s is consistent with the load drawing current through an intermittently failing/high-resistance relay contact, causing the voltage to sag until the arc/contact re-makes. Adjusting the timing potentiometer has no effect, and the input side of the relay shows a clean 12 V, so the issue is not in the sensor or drive electronics but in the relay contact path itself. Replacing/repairing the relay contacts or the immediate series trace/connection to the output (+) cable in the ambient sensor module should restore stable 12 V at the load and eliminate the periodic lamp outages.'
