2026-04-16 12:34:15 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module common negative / ground reference within relay coil and output circuitry'] hypothesis_explanation='All measurements show a consistent ~0.36 V offset between the control module’s local “ground” (relay coil return and output negative reference) and the true battery negative. The power‑supply negative, the control module input −, and the output − cable to the load are all at 0 V with respect to battery negative. However, the relay coil return node and the control module output + node both sit about 0.36 V above this, even though the relay input + is at 11.99 V. This means the relay coil is actually seeing only about 11.63 V, and the output + node to the load only rises to about 0.36 V relative to the true ground, despite the relay contact itself having been verified as healthy.\n\nThe common factor is an internal misconnection or fault in the ambient sensor module’s negative reference: the coil return and the output circuitry are not firmly tied to the incoming 0 V line, but are instead floating about 0.36 V above it through some unintended high‑resistance path or wrong internal wiring (e.g., coil return and output − both connected to a wrong reference node, such as the LED indicator return, rather than to the module’s 0 V terminal). This explains:\n- Why the relay input sees a solid ~12 V from the supply, yet the output + to the load is stuck at ~0.36 V.\n- Why both the coil negative and output − share the same 0.36 V offset.\n- Why adjusting timing and sensitivity potentiometers has no effect on the lamp behaviour.\n\nThus the root cause is a configuration / wiring fault of the ambient sensor module’s internal negative/ground reference network, not the relay contacts themselves. Repair consists of restoring the correct direct connection between the module’s coil/output return node and the input/output − terminals tied to battery negative.'
